<HL>
   Icahn Prepares to Add Condition to Bid:
   The Ouster of Pan Am Chairman Plaskett
   ----
   By Asra Q. Nomani
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 3
</SO>
<CO>
   PN TWA UAL DAL AMR
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   Trans World Airlines owner Carl Icahn is preparing to make
the ouster of Pan Am Corp. Chairman Thomas Plaskett a new
condition for his planned purchase of Pan Am, sources close
to the talks said.
   Such a condition would hurt chances of a friendly
acquisition.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Plaskett's exit is understood to be on a laundry list
of stiff conditions that Mr. Icahn hasn't yet sent to Pan Am;
that list could still be altered before delivery. The
financier is angry at Pan Am for its repeated rebuffs of his
buy-out proposals.
   A Pan Am spokesman said, "Tom Plaskett would not stand in
the way of any offer that could benefit Pan Am or its
constituents."
   Mr. Icahn is proposing to buy Pan Am's 150 million shares
outstanding for $1.50 a share in cash. In addition, the
proposal includes an offer to pay $1 a share in subordinated
notes. The terms of those notes haven't been agreed upon, but
would most likely be valued at much less than $1 a share.
   Pan Am has indicated that it is willing to come to terms
on a merger, but that it requires bridge financing to help
carry operations through the next few months. But Mr. Icahn
has indicated he would give Pan Am such funding only if the
airline holding company first files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
court protection. Pan Am opposes that idea.
   Although he wants Mr. Plaskett removed, Mr. Icahn is
understood to favor retaining Pan Am executives such as
Richard Francis, chief financial officer, and Roger Cooke,
general counsel. Under the plan being considered, Mr. Francis
would apparently run the airline. He has been one of the
chief negotiators with Mr. Icahn and his representatives.
   Mr. Icahn is understood to lack faith in Mr. Plaskett's
management of Pan Am. The TWA camp notes that Pan Am
currently has so little cash that it's unclear whether the
ailing carrier would even have enough money to operate under
Chapter 11.
   Further, in a Christmas Eve letter to Pan Am officials,
Mr. Icahn suggested that Pan Am didn't get the best deal it
could have when it recently agreed to sell desirable
U.S.-London routes for $290 million to UAL Corp.'s United
Airlines.
   Industry observers contend any executive changes at Pan Am
would complicate a merger. "The more conditions placed on the
transaction, the more difficult it is to complete," said
Thomas Longman, an airline analyst at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. in
New York.
   Talks between the two airlines have deteriorated in recent
days, in part because of Mr. Icahn's unconventional
negotiating style, which irritates Pan Am executives. For
instance, they were annoyed when he dispatched his three-page
Christmas Eve letter after they'd left for the day, but in
time for wide distribution to the media. Pan Am officials
viewed that maneuver as a publicity stunt.
   Professional takeover speculators haven't been interested
in following the TWA/Pan Am merger effort because of the
tenuous nature and conditions of the offer as well as Mr.
Icahn's reputation for protracted haggling during
negotiation.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,
Pan Am shares closed unchanged at $1.375 -- less than the
cash portion of Mr. Icahn's proposal.
   Separately, Delta Air Lines said it asked the Department
of Transportation to combine and conduct a hearing on the
international route transfer applications of United and Pan
Am, and of American and TWA. The latter two have also asked
that the cases be consolidated.
   A department spokesman said officials would review the
request. But the department may be unwilling to combine the
cases because that would likely slow down the United-Pan Am
deal. With Pan Am on the ropes financially, its officials
want their transaction completed as soon as possible. The
DOT, in reviewing international route sales, isn't required
to conduct hearings; it just must give interested parties
adequate time to comment.
   Delta said it argued a hearing is necessary to weigh
possible adverse impacts on the industry's competitive
balance. "Delta does not oppose route transfer transactions
in principle," Ronald W. Allen, chairman and chief executive
maintained. "These particular transactions, however, are so
massive that they raise fundamental policy issues affecting
competition and market structure internationally and
domestically." He contended the transfers could create what
he dubbed "a duopoly across the Atlantic," in which the two
largest U.S. airlines would control two-thirds of the nonstop
U.S.-London routes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901228-0035
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901228-0035.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Bond Prices Rise as Record Decline in Orders
   For Durable Goods Underscores Economy's Woes
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Lynn K. Adler
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 31
</SO>
<CO>
   FRE FNM
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
BANKS (BNK)
STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
U.S. GOVERNMENT AGENCY FINANCINGS -- NON-TREASURY (AGN)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bond prices jumped yesterday after the
government reported a record decline in orders for durable
goods.
   The bond market's bellwether 30-year Treasury bond ended
nearly 1/2 point higher, a gain of nearly $5 for a bond with
a $1,000 face amount. The issue's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction of its price, eased to 8.24% from 8.28% on
Wednesday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Prices of tax-exempt municipal bonds, which usually lag
the Treasury market, posted strong gains with some general
obligation bonds issued by Massachusetts climbing as much as
one point. Traders attributed the rise in Massachusetts bonds
to short-covering, where dealers scramble to buy securities
to replace securities they borrowed at an earlier date.
   There also was a flurry of buying in the investment-grade
corporate bond market, which helped to push prices between
1/4 and 3/8 point higher. Mortgage-backed securities rose
between 1/8 and 1/4 point.
   The rally in the bond market was sparked by an extremely
weak economic report. The Department of Commerce reported
that orders for new durable goods plunged 10.5% last month,
offering further evidence that the economy is eroding.
   The decline matched a record drop set last January and was
much deeper than the 2.2% decline that had been forecast by
economists surveyed by Dow Jones Capital Markets Report.
   Bond investors react bullishly to bearish economic news
because slow economic growth often leads to lower interest
rates and lower inflation -- two trends that increase the
value of fixed-income securities.
   The report also set a positive tone for the Treasury's
$8.57 billion auction of four-year notes.
   The average yield set on the notes at yesterday's auction
was 7.66%, sharply lower than the 8.53% average yield at the
previous four-year note auction in September. The average
yield at yesterday's auction was lower than some analysts
expected and was even below the peak when-issued yield of
7.75% set Monday.
   Traders said that prices of notes and bonds were little
changed after the Federal Reserve preannounced, unexpectedly,
that it will execute two-day system repurchase agreements on
Monday. That's a technical trading maneuver designed to add
reserves to the banking system.
   Traders said the Fed made the unusual preannouncement in
an effort to relieve some of the pressures that have been
building in the federal funds market. The federal funds rate,
the rate at which banks charge each other for overnight
loans, hit 100% late Wednesday. The target for the rate is
7%.
   Although the rate often gyrates on the last day of a
two-week bank settlement period, as was yesterday,
Wednesday's spike to 100% was widely viewed in the market as
the result of a serious miscalculation of bank funding needs
by the Federal Reserve.
   While the Fed's announcement may have offered some relief
to the market, it still did not stop the Fed funds rate from
rising far above its target. The rate exceeded 10% yesterday
for some domestic transactions and was far higher on trades
involving some foreign banks.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of
105 16/32, up from 105 1/32 on Wednesday. The issue's yield
fell to 8.24% from 8.28%.
   Treasury bill rates were slightly higher. The discount
rate on three-month bills ended at 6.49% for a
bond-equivalent yield of 6.67%, up slightly from 6.48% to
yield 6.66% on Wednesday. The rate on six-month bills rose to
6.59% to yield 6.89% compared with 6.56% to yield 6.86% on
Wednesday.
   Here are details of yesterday's four-year note auction:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it.
                                                                                                       

                       Four-Year Notes
                                                                                                       

   Applications                          $22,479,102,000
   Accepted bids                          $8,569,307,000
   Accepted at low price                             51%
   Accepted noncompetitively                $643,000,000
   Average price (Rate)                   99.881 (7.66%)

   Low price (Rate)                       99.847 (7.67%)
   Interest rate                                  7 5/8%
                                                                                                       

   The notes are dated Dec. 31, 1990 and mature Dec. 31,
1994.
                                                                                                       

   Corporate &amp; Junk Bonds
                                                                                                       

   A flurry of retail buying enlivened the investment-grade
corporate bond market, injecting a dose of excitement into an
otherwise stultifying week.
   Corporate bond traders said much of the buying was
concentrated in shorter-maturity corporates and high-quality
issues.
   The buying was unexpected since investors typically sell
corporate bonds at year end to clean up their balance sheets
and remove tainted credits.
   "This is the first time in a very long time we've gotten
year-end buying which is causing" yields to fall relative to
yields on Treasury securities, said Andrew Tarica, a
corporate bond trader at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   Mr. Tarica notes that Associates Corp. of North America's
9% five-year notes, which were trading at a yield of about
1.55 percentage points above the comparable Treasury issue
earlier this month, now trade at a spread of about 1.27
percentage points.
   While high-grade corporate bonds ended between 1/4 and 3/8
point higher, junk bonds, or speculative-grade securities
with low credit ratings or no credit ratings at all, finished
only marginally higher.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bonds ended unchanged to 3/8 higher, with some
issues up 1/2 to 1 point.
   Among actively traded secondary issues, the New Jersey
Turnpike Authority's 7.20% securities of 2018 were 3/8
higher, at 99 for a return of 7.26%.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-, Asset-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage securities ended higher.
   Government National Mortgage Association 9% for January
delivery were up 7/32 at 99 4/32. Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp. Gold 9% issues and Federal National Mortgage
Association 9% issues were up 5/32 at 98 24/32 and 98 16/32,
respectively.
   Traders said retail participation has ground to a halt
during the year-end holiday period, as accounts have long
closed their books for the year.
   In the primary market, no new issues were announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901228-0034
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901228-0034.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- American International Group:
   Court Upholds Unit's Fine
   For Liability Overcharges
</HL>
<DATE>
12/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 31
</SO>
<CO>
   AIG
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
PROPERTY &amp; CASUALTY INSURANCE (INP)
</IN>
<LP>
   The state insurance department said the New York State
Court of Appeals upheld a fine against a subsidiary of
American International Group for overcharging taxicab owners
on liability coverage.
   As a result, the AIG unit, Insurance Co. of the State of
Pennsylvania, based in New York, must pay $425,000, the
insurance department said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In May 1988, the subsidiary was fined for overcharging
taxicab mini-fleet owners about $1.4 million over a
three-year period, starting in 1981. The state insurance
department fined the unit for improperly using a liability
conversion factor to increase premiums and increasing
premiums without state approval.
   AIG said the decision puts an end to the "old" case, but
questioned why the Court of Appeals, the state's highest
court, came to the decision without conducting a hearing.
"It's a shame," said Patrick Foley, AIG's general counsel.
"We feel the decision was wrong."
</TEXT>
